Escape: "Every refugee has experience of sexual violence"
Sexual violence is almost part of everyday life for women who flee alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house offers refuge.
Four women sit in a large kitchen.
Each has a baby that is at most one year old.
One has put her little son in her arms.
He looks curiously into the room with big eyes.
His mother stares at the table top.
Until she realizes that she is being observed.
She smiles briefly and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until you speak with Katrin Bahr.
She is General Manager of Condrobs, a social aid provider in Bavaria, and she deals with the topic of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralised accommodations for isolated women and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and the Munich Frauenhilfe.
Recently it was officially opened.
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a guard at the door.
"It is not exaggerated to say that every woman who comes here has had experiences of sexual violence on her flight," says Bahr.
"Men flee because of wars because they are being persecuted politically, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as carriers of hope," she says.
In women, other reasons for escaping prevail: "Many steal away secretly because they see no other way out."
In their homeland they have experienced sexual violence, forced marriages, honour killings, slavery or forced prostitution.
That drives them away.
On the run it goes on.
"That tugs, for example, demand a sexual action for a bottle of water is no rarity," says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Who believes that the end, as soon as they arrive in Germany, is wrong, Bahr tells.
Here too, single women in refugee shelters would often be considered inferior and at worst abused.
This means that about 90 percent of the women living in the accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized, she estimates.
"Some of the children were certainly not voluntarily born".
Many women are used to saying nothing.
"Or they don't dare to speak openly about the experience, because shame is too great".
Since they often do not know how to help, more accommodations are needed only for them, Bahr demands.
In Bavaria, the seven regional governments are responsible for accommodating refugees.
To the question whether they knew about a similar project as in Munich in their area of responsibility, some answer with no.
In Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Even in Swabia, women who have fled alone are not accommodated separately, says Karl Heinz Meyer, spokesman for the government.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower and Middle Franconia there are floors or houses for single women and their children.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodations exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
A study published for the committee says: "It is very important that men and women be accommodated separately."
"If there is no privacy or if men and women are accommodated together, violence against women may continue."
Particularly the washrooms should be separated and easily accessible for women, stands in the study.
