Community, mind, health: Singing is good for seniors
Ursel Kipp has already accompanied her entire life: as a young girl she was in the school choir, as a teacher she studied music, and today the 78-year-old sings in a senior choir.
"Singing moves me - emotionally and physically," she describes.
After a rehearsal, she feels balanced, cheerful and overall more alive, she says.
By the way, she does something good for her health and her mind.
Singing is a great hobby for seniors from several perspectives, says Erhard Hackler of the German Senior League.
Most seniors sing in the choir and share the joy of music with like-minded people, Hackler describes.
Through the regular meeting seniors can establish and maintain social contacts.
Because social and family structures often dissolve in old age, a choir is then an ideal opportunity to spend time with other people.
This experience has also made Ursel Kipp in her choir: "To discuss and organize oneself, to rely on the others and to learn from each other - a choir is a very special form of being together".
Singing can be strenuous in a positive sense, says Hackler.
Because seniors train a deep and controlled breathing.
Those who regularly demand their lungs do not get out of their breath so quickly even in everyday life.
Even when it comes to preserving the sound of the voice in old age, singing is an optimal hobby.
Singing often has a very special effect on older people, says Ursula Lenz of the Federal Association of Elderly Organizations.
In the older generations, singing together was much more important, it was part of everyday life, both in school and in leisure time, she explains.
Lenz often observes that singing or listening to songs arouses many memories in older people, often associated with positive feelings of their youth.
Through lyrics and especially melodies, people who suffer from dementia can imagine long past events.
When singing, the head is also required to perform in a special way, explains Lenz.
To concentrate simultaneously on one ’ s own voice and on a predetermined rhythm and adapt to the other singers – this is a great cognitive challenge.
Especially elderly people who live alone practice not only to concentrate on themselves.
Another positive aspect is the recognition that one experiences through singing in the choir, says Hackler.
An enthusiastic audience is a great praise.
Self-esteem also grows through singing in the choir.
To show oneself: When I practice for a long time, I become better and grow beyond myself - this experience strengthens.
So there are enough good reasons to start singing.
Who wants to try a new hobby, should not hesitate - even if he thinks he has little talent, advises Lenz.
You don't sing alone - with 50 singing people, who already hears when a tone goes by?
In search of the suitable offer seniors have different possibilities, says Hackler.
If someone from the circle of acquaintances in a senior choir, you can simply join.
Many cities also offer overviews of the surrounding choirs.
If you want to sing in an ecclesiastical choir, you can directly contact the congregation or the church leader.
Many senior choirs can also be found on the internet.
Who has no access to the Internet, can ask the family, friends or neighbors for help with the Internet search.
Those who want to sing should definitely join a choir, advises Hackler.
Singing does the soul well and has something liberating - that applies to every age.
