Military leadership falsified ISIS intelligence information, notes Congress Committee
Military members of the United States Central Command changed intelligence information to draw a more optimistic picture of the war against the so-called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, reported an investigative committee of the Congress in a report on Thursday.
The preliminary report, prepared by a task force of the Republican members of the Military Committee, intelligence committees and the Wehrbudgetkommites, reports great dissatisfaction among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors changed their assessments of American efforts in the fight against the Islamic State.
The Central Command, Cencom for short, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, which controls American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence information typically sent by high-level Centcom commanders regularly drew a more positive picture of American efforts against terrorism than allowed by actual conditions on the ground, and were consistently more positive than analyses of other intelligence services," a newspaper article quoted the report.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analyses are presented to our political leaders," noted Ken Calvert, Republican member of the House of Representatives.
The leadership mistakes in Centcom reach to the top of the organization.
The ten-page report shows detailed persistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analyses of American efforts in training Iraqi forces.
Although there is no direct evidence that leaders under Obama have given instructions to change the reports, it shows how analysts saw themselves subjected to pressure from their superiors to draw a more optimistic picture of the threat to the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and statements before the Congress were much more positive than the facts," the report noted.
For example, a Centcom member publicly announced that a military reconquest of Mosul could begin in April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq ’ s second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
"After months of investigation, so much is clear." Mike Pompeo, a Republican Congressman from Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, Central Command leaders changed intelligence reports to downplay ISIS ’ s threat to Iraq.
The Republicans launched the Task Force after they were allotted that analysts were worried about manipulating reports to the Islamic State.
The report published on Thursday will be complemented by more detailed findings while the investigations will continue.
In addition, further investigations of the Centcom reports are under way by the General Inspector of the Ministry of Defence.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee published their own findings on Thursday, in line with some of the Republican Task Force ’ s conclusions.
"In 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an excessively restricted process for the preparation of intelligence assessments on ISIL and Iraqi security services," said the senior democrat in the committee, member of the Adam B. Schiff House of Representatives, in a statement.
This process, according to Mr. Schiff, “delayed the publication of intelligence reports, ” damaged the morality among analysts and“ gave excessively little room for divergent opinions. ”
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats said that they had not found any evidence of White House intervention by Centcom analysts with regard to a "specific political opinion".
The preliminary results of the congress investigations were published on Tuesday by "The Daily Beast".
Last August, the New York Times reported investigations by the Pentagon ’ s inspector general, which were received after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, stated in a statement that the Ministry of Defence would not comment on reports from the Congress, while the investigation of the inspector general was still under way.
But he also stated that "experts sometimes have quite divergent opinions on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence services and the defense ministry welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense."
The investigation has repercussions beyond the question of a successful air campaign under American leadership in Iraq and Syria (a claim made by a growing number of defense officials).
However, last year ’ s accusations raised the question of how President Obama can rely on the Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya, and other crisis regions.
Criticism of secret information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of disagreements over more than ten years ago, when a Centcom analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a document on how, contrary to the recommendations of many analysts, George W. Bush ’ s administration at the time provided for only a small occupying force in Iraq and did not spend much time thinking about the consequences of the 2003 invasion.
