But the newest simulation indicates that Venus could have had a thin, earth-like atmosphere and nevertheless turned slowly.
The model also illuminated the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had more dry areas than Earth, but once had enough water and geographical variability to accommodate life and protect it from rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent matte.
"In the GISS model simulation, the slow rotation of Venus exposes its day side of the Sun for almost two months," said GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release.
This warms the surface and produces rain that creates a thick layer of clouds, which acts as an umbrella to shield the surface from much of the sun ’ s heat.
The result is average temperatures that are some degree cooler than those of Earth today.
The model produced a history of Venus, similar to the evolution previously suspected by planetary researchers.
Although once presumably habitable, Venus -- over several billion years -- has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light.
Their oceans evaporated and their steam was burnt away by ultraviolet light.
When her hydrogen escaped, only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a lethal greenhouse effect remained - Venus, which we know today.
