Kepler measures rotation rate of stars in the star cluster of Pleiades
The latest mission with the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete catalogue of rotation rates under the stars of the star cluster of the Pleiades.
The new data help astronomers to understand why stars rotate at different rates in the cluster of stars, and how the rotation periods are related to the formation of planets.
"We hope to learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age and even the history of its solar system by comparing our results with other star clusters," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a press release.
The star cluster of the Pleiades is 445 light years away from Earth.
Many stars in this cluster, which arose about 125 million years ago, now reach adulthood.
They are now turning the fastest.
These maturing stars emit large amounts of star winds at peak rotation rates.
As these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
When a star age, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by recognizing the time between the appearance of a recognizable star spot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalogue of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars rotate slower than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars with dancers, with larger stars turning slower pirouettes than smaller ones.
"In the" ballet "of the Pleiades we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars," said Rebull.
As the star cluster of the Pleiades is so close, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The star cluster of Pleiades provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older," said Rebull.
There is still a lot ahead of us about which we would like to learn more about how how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rates and hang up their "dance shoes".
Rebull and her colleagues reported in detail in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
