Programmers of blackmail malware currently target companies - and are successful in doing so.
According to a recent survey of malware defense specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America, Great Britain and Germany, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been at least once in the past twelve months, sometimes multiple victims of an attack with blackmail software.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of the companies were already target of ransomware blackmail.
40% of the victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to reuse the attacked systems and data.
According to Malwarebytes observations, the perpetrators are increasingly specializing in attacks in company networks.
If they succeed there, the potentially blackmailed ransom will be significantly higher than with private users.
"We are currently observing a terribly fast evolution of malware," explains Malwarebytes head of the department Marcin Kleczynski in a conversation with the "World".
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send advertising.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
Only private users were the goal, but the change to company attacks took place in the past months frighteningly fast.
Ransomware works for a simple pattern: Once active on the computer of a victim, it searches for recently changed files such as Word, Excel or database and for archives of pictures and videos.
These files encrypt the Ransomware and delete the originals sustainably.
The software then presents the demands of the blackmailers.
In order to get the key code to the files, the victims have to transfer money - mostly in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake with private users, companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project databases without which production is stopped.
Accordingly, the damage is higher if a Ransomware hits.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported sales losses due to Ransomware, 13 percent even had to interrupt business activity completely, in one case people were in danger of life.
In Germany, hospitals have several times been victims of attacks whose patients may be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always say to the victims: Do not pay, you only promote the problem," explains Kleczynski.
But 80 to 90 percent of companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to reject the perpetrators' claim in the face of standstill in operation.
The hackers in turn know this and try everything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, the security researchers at F-Secure have investigated the user interfaces and contact with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion that the perpetrators are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to take more money.
They explain to their victims by chat how they can pay by Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites, or decrypt free example files.
And if private individuals are redeemed after payments of a few hundred euros, companies have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free gains from ransomware blackmail, hackers are becoming more and more professional and share the work, security expert Chester Wisniewski of Antivirus provider Sophos explains: "A single person can write a ransomware about within a week."
It is more likely, however, that they are three or four persons.
The programmers then sell their malware in the form of a software modular to the actual blackmailers.
Malware kits were created by buying the malware itself, advice and additional tools for a one-off fixed price of between $1000 and $10,000.
"Included in the scope of delivery is an adjustment tool so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then seek further hackers to spread the freshly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
You log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from a criminal and ask another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"The criminals usually then commission spammers to spread," explains Wisniewski.
The risk of Ransomware is now known to many companies that better secure their data.
More than 50 percent of companies responsible for IT in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to fend off Ransomware with the help of the backups and scanner software file.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful inspection, the perpetrators will instead threaten the publication of sensitive data, such as customer lists or price calculations," explains Malwarebyte's CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
This means that the damage potential, depending on the type of data, is many times higher than before.
In future, the perpetrators could also grain completely new objectives on the Internet of Things.
At the hacker conference Defcon, security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat connected to the Internet under their control.
In the middle of winter, the activation of such a blocked heater could well be worth a ransom to some victims.
If the perpetrators then instead of the heating in future block an entire production line in a factory, Ransomware could also become a topic in Industry 4.0.
